<font color="#FF0000">THOUGHTS ON WAR &amp; PEACE</font><br>
<tt>Sun Mar  2 16:09:05 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
Lucien,<br>
     Am reminded when St. Francis of Assisi went to Egypt to preach before the Sultan.  After treating Francis to the standard &quot; an infidel like you has some nerve coming here with the French Army on our shores&quot; rhetoric in front of his courtiers; he took Francis aside privately and said that he had to be rough publicly, but honored and respected Francis as a man of peace. He went on though to say: &quot;As long as the world is the way it is; there will be need of men of war like me.&quot;  <br><br>
Men crave peace, but practice Clausewitz, as in: &quot;War is an extension of politics by other means.&quot;  The more frustration with the situation, the more extreme the &quot;other means&quot;.  Those who lack the means for open warfare resort to terrorism.  We live in a paradox this century; when hardly anyone sees war as a good thing in itself, but has far surpassed any previous time in the savagery and moral bankruptcy of its warfare.
<p><code>-- gerald_ney@icpphil.navy.mil  (Gerald Ney, &quot;the Herd&quot;  7/68-7/69) </code><p>


